# DAA Complete System — Interactive Algorithm Visualizer

A single-file interactive web application covering all five units of Design and Analysis of Algorithms. Built with vanilla HTML, CSS, and JavaScript — no frameworks, no build tools, no dependencies.

## Live Demo
Open `daa-system.html` directly in any modern browser. No server required.

## What's Inside

### Unit 2 — Brute Force
- **Linear Search** — O(n) scan with early exit
- **Bubble Sort** — O(n²) with swapped-flag early exit optimization (O(n) best case)
- **Selection Sort** — O(n²) always, minimum n−1 swaps

### Unit 3 — Divide & Conquer
- **Binary Search** — O(log n), overflow-safe mid formula
- **Merge Sort** — O(n log n) stable, single temp[] allocation (no GC storms)
- **Quick Sort** — O(n log n) avg, Median-of-Three pivot + Insertion Sort hybrid for n≤16

### Unit 4 — Greedy Strategy
- **Adaptive Algorithm Selector** — a greedy meta-algorithm that probes O(√n) samples,
  computes presortedness and entropy, then greedily selects the optimal sorter.
  Demonstrates the Greedy Choice Property: local optimal = global optimal for this problem class.

### Unit 5 — Limitation Analysis & NP-Hardness
- Algorithm breakdown cards (worst cases, memory limits, engineering fixes)
- **Breaking Point Simulator** — visual chart showing where naive Quick Sort degrades vs.
  the optimized version across n = 100 to 1,000,000
- Complexity comparison table (all 6 algorithms + Java's TimSort)
- P vs NP vs NP-Hard classification

### Benchmark
- Runs all algorithms in-browser against `Array.prototype.sort()` (TimSort equivalent)
- Methodology: warmup runs + median of 5 timed trials + `performance.now()` at nanosecond precision
- Separate sorting and searching benchmarks
- Configurable: array size, distribution (random/nearly-sorted/reverse), warmup count, target position
- Pie charts showing time share and comparison counts independently

## Design Highlights
- **Zero dependencies** — Chart.js from CDN, everything else is native
- **Data-driven rendering** — algorithm data is plain objects; renderers are generic
- **Cooperative async animation** — `async/await` + `sleep()` yields to the browser event loop
- **Synchronized highlighting** — step cards and code lines highlight together
- **CSS design system** — all colors and themes are CSS custom properties
- **Statistically rigorous benchmark** — median-of-5, separate warmup, nanosecond precision

